04387nam a22006375i 9780231554169DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20232023nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2022040560  a97802315541697 a10.7312/zryd201562doi  a(DE-B1597)653712  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPN1998.3.F726 4aPN1998.3.F726bZ79 2023 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a791.43/6110973223/eng/202212081 aZryd, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHollis Frampton :bNavigating the Infinite Cinema /cMichael Zryd. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: From the Chemistry of Cobalt to the Chemistry of Dirt -- t1. A Brief Introduction to Frampton’s Films Before Magellan -- t2. An Introduction to Magellan -- t3. Metahistory and the Archive: “Historical Necessity” and Tradition -- t4. Encyclopedism, the Universe, and Everything -- t5. Archaeology: Millennial Allegories of Art, Representation, and Politics in the Camera Arts -- t6. The Constellation -- tConclusion: Virtual Future Metahistory -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHollis Frampton was an American filmmaker, photographer, and theorist who bridged the experimental film and contemporary art worlds in the 1960s and 1970s. Best known for avant-garde films including Zorns Lemma (1970) and (nostalgia) (1971), Frampton spent his later years working on the unfinished epic Magellan, a monumental cycle that used the metaphor of Ferdinand Magellan’s circumnavigation of the world to rethink the natures and meanings of history, modernity, and cinema. Frampton’s career was cut short by cancer at age 48, with his vast ambitions for the project left incomplete.This book is a groundbreaking and comprehensive account of this remarkable figure’s work in its totality, from Frampton’s earliest films through Magellan. Michael Zryd explores the connections linking Frampton’s art and thought to other media forms, histories, and cultural frameworks. He foregrounds Frampton’s notion of the “infinite cinema,” which redefined the parameters of the medium to encompass all forms of moving image and sound media across the past and future of cinematic possibility. Zryd analyzes Frampton’s ambivalent relationship with modernism and the Enlightenment, showing how the artist navigated between attraction to radical artistic investigation and awareness of this tradition’s implication in colonialism and other oppressive power structures. Shedding new light on Frampton’s project of exploring and critiquing how cinema attempts to capture and understand the world, this book also considers his significance for contemporary art.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aExperimental filmszUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aFrampton, Hollis,d1936-1984xCriticism and interpretation. 0aMotion picture producers and directorszUnited StatesvBiography. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/zryd2015640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231554169423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231554169/original  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK